learned_story: In Uganda, people fear the police (the Uganda police). When you are viewed with the police or at a police station, you're always tagged to be a criminal or in trouble with the law. During fieldwork, I have been able  to overcome this fear and freely interact with police officials and reach  ranks and offices I wouldn't,  thanks to Speak Up Project. Rosemary
fav_moment: Telling the policemen or drivers that Speak Up is a  countrywide road safety pilot project and not covering just a small region within Uganda.
field_challenge: The challenge with accomodation;  I went to  a certain guesthouse  since it was late and it seemed it was the only good one available . I had no option even if electricity was off and there was no water. I was provided with a candle and a jerry can filled with water and I thought  it was okay for a night. However, my little relief was interrupted by a midnight  guest who didn't fear to visit even with the candle light on. I was I woken by the rat that kept running around my face... like inspecting. At first I  thought it was an insect, preferably  a stubborn mosquito that had hidden itself inside the mosquito. To my owlful astonishment, it was s little rat!!!!!!What I night  !!!!

trainingimprove: 1. The training should be extended for at least three days.2. During the training some time should be allocated to the supervisors to specifically evaluate the enumerators to make sure they are knowledgeable enough before setting off for field.
skills_other: Project management software, blogging  and content management software
learned_story: Conflict Resolution.While in field, a friend of mine who was on a different team by then called me to address issues- that to my knowledge were  meant for supervisors. This was response " First,  I appreciate your call and concerns but I wish to state that if you have any issues, address them to your supervisor who will then talk to me at a supervisory level.  I acknowledge that we are friends but in this case, please respect hierarchy.  If they are any personal issues that you would wish to share with me, feel free to call me. Thank you". I shared this with some of  fellow supervisors who said it  was a more assertive manner of reducing  Inter-team rumour mongering.Story by Blaise Mwesiga
fav_moment: While working with my team and the Interns in Kigezi region, all officers treated us with utmost respect and urgency. The team was no longer team but family so th eery changed the name from Team west to Team best internally. As away of saying  goodbye to the Interns and appreciating my team, I took them sheepishly for  a boat ride at Lake Bunyonyi even with the water phobic individuals like myself. A few days after their return, we visited the famous AMABERE GA NYINA MWIRU in Fort portal _ on the eve of 25th, the suprised me with a birthday. To get me out of bed, one of my famous actors" Fara- name assumed" came to my room shouting- Blaise! Blaise!we have an emergency,    Yuou,  on of the Interns has been knocked by aboda boda and was bleeding profusely ! We don't know what to do!" He kept repeating the same until his voice could no longer be heard.  I came shouting ....what! Oh my God!Lights off and then on at the hotel reception and there goes our famous song ...happy birthday......
field_challenge: We used a Noah as a means of transportation, had extra passengers seated in the boot facing the emergency door, nicknamed the driver as Chairman,  went on deducting coins on  transport fares every time  he hit a pothole, drove us until fairly like driving at a high speed or in a wrong lane until we had to pay half the agreed amount.
pm_comments: Thanks to everyone.Thanks again
finalendcomments: My special thanks to the Project Manager for her dedication,  commitment and outstanding principles
